  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Video animation on homecare for older people: COVID 19</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">It is now known that older persons (especially the older old) face a much higher risk of dying from COVID-19 than the general population, as do those with underlying health conditions. An early study from China&apos;s National Health Commission suggested that about 80 per cent of people who died from the virus in China were over the age of 60, and 75 per cent had pre-existing conditions. We find similar patterns in European countries.
Older people who are dependent on carers and living in care homes are far more at risk as they can only have limited isolation and are in close contact with care providers on a daily basis. Care homes have become hotbeds for COVID-19 infections in many parts of the world. Asia is expecting to follow the similar trends.

There are more than 2,000 care homes, both institutional and informal in South East Asia. In South Asia, India alone has around 40,000 care homes in the country. Another group of older people who need special care is those living in their community and receiving home and social care from community volunteers. Providing information and guidelines to centarl governments or throough websites is important but insufficient. The messages have to reach all echelons of the care suystems. So, simple presentation of the topic and smart dissemination are crucial. HelpAge plans to develop two video animation to provide simple, clear guidelines to care homes and community care in the context of COVID-19.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To provide simple and clear guidelines for home-based care
organisers and providers at community levels, preventing infection and

maintaining carers and cared safe</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To provide simple and clear guidelines on how to protect older
people in care homes, preventing infection and maintaining carers and

cared safe</narrative>
  </description>
